                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote type="miniature">
                        <p>Fol. 8v: A miniature, a <term>Calvarie group</term> a representation of
                           Christ on the cross with Virgin Mary and John the Apostle on each side of
                           him. The miniature is printed in <bibl>
                              <ref target="CCIsl7">Icelandic Illuminated Manuscripts of the Middle
                                 Ages</ref>
                              <note>Plate 13.</note>
                           </bibl>
                        </p>
                     </decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>
                  <additions><p>On fol. 1r pen trials, names etc. are found.</p>
                     <p>In the calendar obituaries from the <date notBefore="1600" notAfter="1699"
                           >seventeenth century</date> referring to a fair number of ancestors and
                        other relatives of the priest of <name type="place">Skinnastaðir</name>,
                           <name type="person" key="EinNik003">Einar Nikulásson</name>
                     </p>
                     <p>On the originally blank fol. 8r, Stefán Karlsson (cf. <bibl>
                           <ref type="secondary-1" target="MarOve2003">Overgaard 2003</ref>
                           <biblScope unit="pages">197</biblScope>
                        </bibl>) has succeeded in deciphring an almost eligible note by the aid of
                        ultra violet light: <q>Eirikur bonde lopz s<supplied reason="illegible"
                              >on</supplied> h<supplied reason="illegible">e</supplied>f<ex>er</ex>
                           gefet iungfru mar<lb/>iu  munka þ<supplied reason="illegible"
                              >uer</supplied>
                           <gap reason="illegible"/> sal<supplied reason="illegible">tara</supplied>
                           sier til salu <lb/> hialp<ex>ar</ex> u<ex>ar</ex> þa lieded fr<supplied
                              reason="illegible">a</supplied> hingad burdi uors her<ex>r</ex>a <lb/>
                           ihesu <ex>christ</ex>i þusund cccc hundrud sextiu ok niu <lb/> är</q>
                     </p>
                     <p>Most of 8r is taken up by a <q xml:lang="is">mäldägi hlydär kirkiv</q> -
                        concerning the church of <name type="place">Reykjahlíð</name>, near Mývatn
                           (<name type="place" key="SuðÞin01">Suður-Þingeyjarsýsla</name>): <q
                           xml:lang="is">A eidu<ex>m</ex>
                           <date when="1573-02-17">17 dag februarij 1573</date></q> (a diplomatic
                        transcription is found in <bibl><ref target="MarOve2003">Overgaard
                              2003</ref><biblScope unit="pages">218</biblScope></bibl>). Above this,
                        four erased lines written in an older hand containing an account etc. are
                        found.</p>
                  </additions>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin><p>Written in <origPlace>Iceland</origPlace> in <origDate notBefore="1350"
                           notAfter="1399" resp="MarOve2003">the second half of the fourteenth
                           century</origDate>. Based on the text on fol. 8r, it can be inferred that <name
                           type="person" key="EirLop001">Eiríkur Loptsson</name> of Grund presented
                        the manuscript in <date when="1469">1469</date> to the Virgin Mary of <name
                           type="org">Munkaþverá</name>. According to Overgaard it is possible that
                        the manuscript was intended for Eiríkurs grandmother, Sofía
                        Eiríksdóttir.</p>
                     <p>Of the Latin Psalter <name type="person" key="ArnMag001">Árni
                           Magnússon</name> mentions on the AM-slip, only fifteen leaves now remain.
                        Eleven of these were used as binding material for manuscripts (now
                        transferred to <ref type="ms" target="Acc-0007-d-en">Acc 7d</ref>, Psalter
                        VII) and four for printed books (now in <name type="org" key="KB">The Royal
                           Library</name> of <name type="place" key="Copen01"
                        >Copenhagen</name>).</p></origin>
                  <provenance><p>As stated above, most of the numerous obituaries of the calendar
                        refer to relatives of the priest of <name type="place">Skinnastaðir</name>,
                           <name type="person" key="EinNik003">Einar Nikulásson</name>. In all
                        probability the manuscript came into his family's possession shortly after
                        the Reformation and was passed on from generation to generation until
                        acquired by <name type="person" key="ArnMag001">Árni
                     Magnússon</name>.</p></provenance>

               </history>
